<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="465" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,766,1045]" pageId="1" pageNumber="465">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,766,792]" pageId="1" pageNumber="465">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1803" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[281,387,767,792]" class="Insecta" family="Psilidae" genus="Loxocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="465" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis box="[281,387,767,792]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="465">Loxocera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[395,455,767,793]" pageId="1" pageNumber="465" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in its current sense can be recognized within 
<taxonomicName box="[973,1062,767,793]" class="Insecta" family="Psilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="465" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Psilidae</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of character states: frontal vitta desclerotized, dull and velvety; lunule sclerotized, broadly exposed between antennal base and anterior margin of frons; fore wing with alula glabrous except margin; hind femur with a subapical patch of microtomentum on ventral surface; male sternite 8 broadly exposed and setulose, fused to tergite 6 and epandrium; female tergite 10 and cerci separated. For details on the character states used to define the subgenus see 
<bibRefCitation author="Buck, M. &amp; Marshall, S. A." pageId="1" pageNumber="465" pagination="193 - 219" refId="ref3578" refString="Buck, M. &amp; Marshall, S. A. (2006 b) Revision of New World Loxocera (Diptera: Psilidae), with phylogenetic redefinition of Holarctic subgenera and species groups. European Journal of Entomology, 103, 193 - 219. https: // doi. org / 10.14411 / eje. 2006.022" type="journal article" year="2006">Buck &amp; Marshall (2006b)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,766,1045]" pageId="1" pageNumber="465">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,517,982,1009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="465">Diversity and distribution.</emphasis>
This subgenus currently contains 10 species, 7 of which are distributed in the Palearctic Region, and 3 species occur in the northern part of the Oriental Region.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
